  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "The national rate is stable, but use is shifting toward modern methods",
        "body": "Among all women aged 15 to 49, contraceptive use was almost unchanged: 33.8 percent in 2025, compared with 34.1 percent in 2022. The more important movement is inside that total. Modern method use rose from 24.3 to 25.7 percent, while traditional method use fell from 9.8 to 8.1 percent. Implants and injectables gained ground, while withdrawal declined. The data point to a gradual change in method mix rather than a broad expansion in use."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional variation is one of the strongest patterns",
        "body": "Contraceptive use among all women ranges widely across regions. Davao Region had the highest use at 45.1 percent, followed by Eastern Visayas, Caraga, MIMAROPA, Central Luzon, and SOCCSKSARGEN, all near or above 39 percent. BARMM was far lower at 16.2 percent, while Central Visayas and NCR were also below 30 percent. The distance between Davao Region and BARMM is 28.9 percentage points, making the regional spread almost as large as the national level itself."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Modern and traditional use have different regional centers",
        "body": "The highest-use regions are not high for the same reasons. Davao Region leads overall use and also has the highest modern method use, at 37.1 percent. MIMAROPA, SOCCSKSARGEN, and Caraga also stand out for modern methods. Traditional method use is concentrated elsewhere, led by Eastern Visayas at 12.1 percent, Ilocos Region at 11.8 percent, and Western Visayas at 10.8 percent. Regional use is therefore as much about method mix as it is about the total level."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Use is concentrated in the main family-building ages",
        "body": "Use rises sharply across the life course. It is 3.1 percent among women aged 15-19, then reaches 53.9 percent at ages 35-39 before falling at ages 45-49. The number-of-living-children pattern is even steeper: 4.2 percent among women with no living children compared with 66.8 percent among women with three or four living children. The direction is expected, but the size of the difference is analytically important."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Social gradients need careful reading in the all-women denominator",
        "body": "Use is higher among women with Grades 1-6 education at 47.9 percent than among women with Grades 11-12 at 15.2 percent. It is also higher in the lowest wealth quintile at 39.6 percent than in the highest at 28.4 percent. These patterns do not read like a simple social advantage gradient. Because this page covers all women aged 15 to 49, subgroup differences partly reflect where women are in the family-building years, not only social or economic position."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Contraceptive use among all women was nearly unchanged from 2022 to 2025, but modern methods gained share as traditional methods declined.",
      "Regional variation is large, with use ranging from 45.1 percent in Davao Region to 16.2 percent in BARMM.",
      "Modern and traditional use peak in different places, so regional method mix matters as much as the total rate."
    ]
  }
